pros:
Good cause;
Good location;
Has grown over the years and increased services;
Some nice people who do put in efforts.

cons:
1. Unfortunately Hestia is very out of date, the senior team just want information all the time, the way it has to be prepared is in relying on very poor systems so much so that it takes longer to do summaries than actions;
2. There is a culture of fear but it’s because the senior team and the Chief Executive do not have the technical knowledge, many staff with the right skills and competence have left, it is very departmental and there is a lot of red tape, I have seen staff paid off;
3. There is a lot of wastage in which a lot of options chosen have not been cost effective e.g. hiring externally and when hired some get away with extending the time to extract fees;
4. It is a cross between Kids Company scandal and St Mungos strikes, a lot of staff are tired of being bullied due to having to keep justifying what they are doing, there are other staff who don’t receive any training at all and are setup to fail;
5. The Chief Exec’s tactic is to rely on petty and trivial methods to instil fear, he is someone who doesn’t allow questions to be asked at him at conference as he knows he will be confronted with a lot of bad questions;
6. The process in investigating staff for any potential misconduct is an abuse of process, I’ve seen HR make up their mind on decisions without any investigation;
7. Many parts of the business can be short staffed, you are expected to work beyond the 39 hour contract if full time;
8. There is manipulating of data in order to win contracts.
